{
  "texts": [
    "Finally, SBST cannot effectively handle interactions with the external environment (e.g., databases, network services, or the file system) because the behavior of these interactions cannot be quantified to guide the fitness function [45].Symbolic and Concolic Execution.",
    "Symbolic execution offers a more systematic, formalmethods-based alternative [13,169].",
    "Instead of concrete values, it executes a program with symbolic variables as inputs and collects path constraints along the way.",
    "By solving these constraints with a constraint solver (e.g., an SMT solver), it can precisely generate inputs that trigger specific program paths.",
    "While theoretically rigorous, symbolic execution suffers from the path explosion problem, where the number of feasible execution paths grows exponentially with program size, rendering exhaustive exploration computationally infeasible."
  ]
}